04681nam a22007695i 9781787445772DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874457727 a10.1515/97817874457722doi  a(DE-B1597)676033  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aDC33.4b.G455 2020 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a944.0342231 aGelléri, Gábor, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLessons of Travel in Eighteenth-Century France :bFrom Grand Tour to School Trips /cGábor Gelléri. 1aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (245 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in the Eighteenth Century ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on translations -- tIntroduction: on reading arts of travel -- t1 Defining the Grand Tour -- t2 From touring to training: the case of diplomacy, 1680–1830 -- t3 Trading with men, dealing with God: abbé Pluche’s ideas on travel -- t4 Travelling on a Moebius strip: Émile’s travels -- t5 The end of an era? The prize contest of the Academy of Lyon (1785–1787) -- t6 Inventing school trips? Revolutionary programmes of collective educational travel -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA study of the literature of the 'art of travel' in eighteenth-century France, showing how consideration of who should travel and for what purpose provided an occasion for wider debate about the social status quo.Early modern educational travel is usually associated with the Grand Tour: a young nobleman's journey through the established highlights of Europe. Lessons of Travel presents how, in eighteenth-century France, this practicewas heavily contested, and the idea of educational travel had far wider implications. Through the study of a huge range of both canonical and little-known sources discussing "the art of travel", from abbé Pluche's educational best seller, The Spectacle of Nature, through Rousseau's Émile to practical prospectuses for collective educational travel in the revolutionary period, Gelléri investigates what it meant to 'think about travels' ineighteenth-century France. Consideration of who should travel and for what purpose, he argues, contributed to an international intellectual tradition but also provided a pretext for debate on the social status quo, including suchissues as the place of the merchant class, the necessity for professional training, the uses of travel for young women and the education of a new generation of citizens of the Revolution. GÁBOR GELLÉRI is Lecturer in French at Aberystwyth University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdult educationxHistoryy18th century. 0aFrance-Intellectual life-18th century. 0aGrand tours (Education). 0aTravelxHistoryy18th century. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aFrench Studies. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  a16th century.  a17th century.  a18th century.  a19th century.  aEnlightenment.  aFrance.  aGrand Tour.  aJean-Jacques Rousseau.  aPluche.  aRousseau.  aTravel.  aars apodemica.  aart of travel.  ade Genlis.  aeducation.  aeducational travel.  aphilosophy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787445772?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787445772423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787445772/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles